'\" t
.TH "vTTY" "7" "" "vtty"
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.SH "NAME"
vTTY - User session terminal session
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.B vtty
is very similar to
.BR uvtty (7)
only a vTTY runs as system services, instead of as a user. Namely a
.BR socat (1)
server, of which instead of the user's desired shell, it starts a getty
in the backend service on the pty, of which runs as root, and the
.BR socat (1)
client that runs under the
.BR foot (1)
terminal emulator, of which runs under wlroots-based
.BR cage (1)
Wayland server, that runs in the frontend service, that runs as a
non-root system user.
.SH "STARTING"
The vtty units are parameterized systemd units, but Starting the
frontend service starts the backend service. The parameter is the seat
name of which to start the frontend on, until the next (optional)
instance name for that seat. For example:
.RS 4
systemctl start vtty-frontend@seat0.service
.RE
starts on
.B seat0
and
.RS 4
systemctl start vtty-frontend@seat0@instance1.service
.RE
will also start an instance on
.B seat0
but the service instance name will be
.B seat0@instance1
so that multiple instances of vTTYs can be started on one seat.
.PP
The instance name portion is not treated specially by the vTTYs, but it
does allow multiple instances to be managed, and started on a single
seat.
.BR vtty-seatmanager (8)
does so by naming its instances
.B vtty1,
.B vtty2,
and so on.
.SH "STARTING OTHER DISPLAY SERVERS"
It is possible to start display servers, (or anything that uses
/dev/dri/cardX or /dev/fbX) from a vTTY using the
.BR vtty-launch (1)
command. The frontend is temporarily suspended by
.B vtty-launch
to allow the desired program to take control, such as
.B startx
or
.B weston
and the like.
.SH "REPLACING autovt@.service"
On kernels that still have VTs, it is possible to link
.B vtty-frontend-vt@.service
as
.B autovt@.service
to replace the kernel console. However
.B vtty-launch
will \fBnot\fR work on seats \fBwith\fR VTs.
.SH "ACCESSIBILITY"
.B vtty
supports an optional accessible mode, where all the text is
read by the fenrir screen reader.
.SH "CONFIGURATION"
.PP
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/kanshiconfig.conf
is the configuration file for a small daemon that ensures that
.BR cage (1)
uses clone mode.
.PP
By creating a
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/accessiblemode
file. (it can be empty), enables the accessible mode.
.PP
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/footkiosk.conf
is the configuration for the
.BR foot (1)
terminal emulator.
.PP
The directory
.B @sysconfdir@/vtty/
is set as
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME
so that any other library configuration files, like
.B ~/.config/xkb
can be set by an administrator. This is applicable to the frontend
only, not the user processes running on the backend service.
.PP
Adding a
.B vtty-login-program
to the
.B $PATH
overrides the usage of getty, and the vtty instead starts that. It can be a symlink to another binary, such as
.B console-conf
.SH "BOOT OPTIONS"
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkblayout=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBLAYOUT
for the vTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkbmodel=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBMODEL
for the vTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkbvariant=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBVARIANT
for the vTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vconsole.xkboptions=
.RS 12
Sets
.B XKBOPTIONS
for the vTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B vttyaccessible
.RS 12
Enables accessibility mode for the vTTYs.
.RE
.IP \[bu]
.B novttyaccessible
.RS 12
Disables accessibility mode for for the vTTYs. This always takes
precedence so that in case there is a problem with
.BR fenrir (1)
the system is not unusable.
.RE
.SH NOTES
Only the first GPU in the seat is used. The vTTYs will not span to screens on the second card.
.SH See Also:
.BR vtty-launch (1)
